Transportation network design¶

Let's imagine that a famous tycoon named Melon Mask has completed his new invention: the hypermegaminiloop. That revolutionizes urban transportation, but at the moment it is very expensive.

The mayor of New York has found out about it and wants to be an early adopter of the project and complement (not replace) its transportation network. For this, data is available from Uber demand that this new method is intended to cover.

A representative but smaller subset of the data is given to prevent its processing from having very long execution times.

a. Stops Location: clustering¶

The first part of the design of the transportation network is to locate the future stops. To do this, you will have to identify between 100 and 200 places on the map (approximation provided by the city's transportation department) with a high concentration of demand. You can choose any clustering algorithm for this task, but remember that you will have to justify the answer for the project proposal.

Implementation: choose and apply a clustering technique to find between 100 and 200 groups of points.

Analysis: Facing the drafting of the project proposal, why did you choose this clustering method?

The clustering method chosen is DBSCAN. As mentioned in the statement, the stops must be located in places with a high concentration of demand, therefore, DBSCAN is suitable for this type of problem since the clusters would be formed based on the density of the points where there is more demand for uber trips . This differs from the use of K-Means, a method that would generate a previously determined number of clusters based on the Euclidean distance, without taking density/demand into account.

lon_max = df[['Lon', 'DBSCANClusters']].groupby(by=["DBSCANClusters"]).max()

#Calculate the difference of the minimun and maximun latitude and longitude. 
#Transformed to meters (one degree of latitude equals 111 km and one degree of longitude is around 75 km)
Diff_Lat_km = (lat_max - lat_min) * 111
Diff_Lon_km = (lon_max - lon_min) * 75

#Multiply the values of the difference of latitudes and longitudes to get the Areas. Put it in the new dataframe.
df_Clusters["Area"] = Diff_Lat_km["Lat"]*Diff_Lon_km["Lon"]

#Rename the column Base

Analysis: Do you observe any suspicious situation? Analyze it and, if necessary, clean the data for the following steps.

Yes, I do. There was an issue with the distance in degrees, because we got the difference of the latitude and longitude values, but it was not in meters or kilometers. So, I converted the degrees to kilometers. One degree of latitude is 111 km and one degree of longitude at New York is about 75 km. Although the areas of the clusters do not reach 1 square km, I decided to use this measure, otherwise the numbers were too small to be understandable.

Source: https://www.sco.wisc.edu/2022/01/21/how-big-is-a-degree/

c. Transportation network design¶

Because the technology is very new and expensive, we have the mandate to make a design that minimizes the extension of the network trying to cover the largest number of requests possible.

Various strategies can be used for this. Among them is the MST or Minimum Spanning Tree family, with algorithms such as Kruskal or Prim. The Kruskal algorithm has the advantage of being very fast because it is greedy (suboptimal) and, furthermore, it avoids cycles. An extra benefit, since in our case it would establish redundant links, which we want to avoid due to the high cost.

The steps are the following:

  1. Prepare the data for the graph.
  2. Apply the Kruskal algorithm.
  3. Analyze the results and decide the final design of the network.

1. Prepare the data for the graph.

Implementation: create a dataframe in which there is one row per cluster and it contains: id of the cluster (numeric), latitude and longitude (representative of the cluster), and number of points belonging to the cluster.

2. Apply the Kruskal algorithm.

To create the undirected graph (if 1 is connected to 2, the reverse direction is assumed) from which the Kruskal algorithm will select the links, it is necessary to indicate the possible edges of the graph.

To create the graph, simply instantiate the Graph class of the kruskal module that we have modified from here. Indicating in the vertex parameter of its constructor the highest id of cluster +1. Subsequently, edges can be added to the graph, indicating first the two cluster ids that the section joins and finally their weight, which is indicated by the definition of weight later on.

Finally, the result of Kruskal is calculated over the graph by calling the kruskal method, which also has a max_links parameter if we only want as many links to be generated as indicated (useful later).

A concrete example would be the following:

g = kruskal.Graph(vertex=5)
g.add_edge(0, 1, 8)
...
g.add_edge(3, 4, 7)
g.kruskal()

Due to the high cost, it is necessary to justify the construction of each section of the hypermegaminiloop, so we are going to use a measure that weighs (weight) each section (union between any 2 clusters $i$ and $j$):

$$weight(i, j) = -\frac{n_i+n_j}{dist(i, j)}$$

Where:

  • $n_i$ is the number of points in cluster $i$, in the same way $n_j$ is the number of points in cluster $j$.
  • $dist(i, j)$ is the geographic distance in km between the center of cluster $i$ and cluster $j$.

The geographical distance between any 2 points is not the Euclidean distance, since the earth has curvature. For this you can use the module haversine (already imported as hs at the beginning of the assignment).

Finally, note that the final weight is negative because the Kruskal algorithm sees this weight as a cost that it tries to minimize. For our part, we want to encourage that the higher the ratio described, the more attractive it is to Kruskal, which is why it becomes negative.

Implementation: create a graph following the example code in which all the pairs of possible clusters appear (it is not necessary to repeat the pairs because it is an undirected graph where A-B is also equal to B-A), where the weight (last parameter of the add_edge method ) is calculated as described in the weight formula.
In [204]:
#Weight Function
def weight(i, j):
    
    #Number of points in two clusters
    n1 = dfMST2["NumPoints"][dfMST2.index == i].item()
    n2 = dfMST2["NumPoints"][dfMST2.index == j].item()
    
    #Distance(i, j)
    point1 = (dfMST2['Lat'][dfMST2.index == i].item(), dfMST2['Lon'][dfMST2.index == i].item())
    point2 = (dfMST2['Lat'][dfMST2.index == j].item(), dfMST2['Lon'][dfMST2.index == j].item())
    haversine = hs(point1, point2)
    
    result = -(n1+n2)/haversine
    return result

  
#Apply of the kruskal algorithm
g = kruskal.Graph(vertex=145)

for i in range(145):
    for u in range(145):
        if (i < u):  #To avoid repetition
            g.add_edge(i, u, weight(i, u))

g.kruskal()

krus = g.kruskal()

#Create a new column with the weight in positive numbers.
krus["weight_positive"] = -krus["weight"]

for num in range(len(krus)):
    c1 = krus.loc[[num]]['id_a'].item()
    c2 = krus.loc[[num]]['id_b'].item()
    line = (krus.loc[[num]]["weight_positive"].item() - krus["weight_positive"].min()) / (krus["weight_positive"].max() - krus["weight_positive"].min())
    
    x1 = dfMST2.loc[[c1]]['Lon'].item()
    y1 = dfMST2.loc[[c1]]['Lat'].item()
    
    x2 = dfMST2.loc[[c2]]['Lon'].item()
    y2 = dfMST2.loc[[c2]]['Lat'].item()
    
    plt.plot([x1,x2], [y1,y2], linewidth=line*2, color='b')
